I was listening to Tour by Macky Gee 17 times in a row, and I came across a number of people talking shit on him and this genre they call 'jump up'. I listened to many examples of """good""" DnB and other similar genres and all of them bored me shitless. The sound design is great and the layering is is dense and complex and the songs are fucking tedious.

The thing about music is it's not about making sounds that sound good, but rather making sounds that make you feel good. Or even sad or whatever, but just feel something. When that bass comes in on Tour you just go oh fucking hell that is the one. It doesn't need to be some great intellectual pursuit, it has a predictable buildup and then just repeats the same fucking thing for like 4 minutes straight, and why???? Because it sounds fucking sick.

The electronic scene has lost sight of this. Everything is about retardedly complex sound design and no one ever actually makes engaging music with all these ridiculous sounds.

The problem is that a German original translated to French translated to English.

"L´armee de ceux qui sont tombeés n´a pas rendu les armes,elle marche das le rang des soldats"

this could be roughly translated as
"the army of those who have fallen, has not put down (or back) its weapons, it marches within the ranks of our soldiers"

Initially, this sentence and its symbolism is rooted in the so called Horst Wessel Lied, the unofficial Nazi Germany hymn...Horst Wessel was shot by communists in 1930, and it was notably Joseph Goebbels who made him the ulimate martyr for Nazi Germany, and JG was also responsible for a wide distribution of the Horst Wessel Lied. For anyone interested in Germany it is very well known that the Horst Wessel Lied and main symbolisms used by Goebbels are tighly linked with each other.

posts.sub: Schizo Theory - NPCs Can't Listen to Music
posts.com:
I firmly believe that the same way most people can't visualize an apple in their head, plenty more lack the ability to process what they're actually hearing in music.

When the average person listens to a song, they do not hear individual instruments interacting, but the song as its own entity, as if it's not just a collection of sounds but a new thing entirely. It's correct that most songs are the sum of their parts, but that's not my point. I mean that, if you were to ask the typical music listener to single out a passage or listen for specific sounds in a song, they genuinely cannot accomplish this simple task. This is the real reason a lot of music "analysis" is just giving subjective opinions and barely talking about the actual music.

To demonstrate how much of an issue this is, let's look at a Pokémon battle theme. Yes, I'm using VGM to explain my point on /mu/, just humor me here https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h_E5aMbNoug

Listen to this song and try to only follow the bassline. What you'll notice immediately is that you're picking up on every little thing that happens in it naturally. This isn't something you learn in music theory, nor is it something you even have to actively do. It's completely natural, as in our ears point us towards lower frequencies before anything else.

Not for NPCs, however. Something is incredibly off with their hearing, maybe due to genetics or noise pollution or SOMETHING, but they do not ever notice the bassline by itself, or connect the trumpets to the piano which comes in later. They probably can't even recognize when the song loops until the melody starts back over again, they have to be explicitly made to look for these things. Why am I using Pokémon here? Because think about it, this is a song someone will hear potentially THOUSANDS of times over the course of a playthrough, and barely anybody can remember how it goes. They hear the opening, have a faint recollection of the main passages, and that's really it.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114607346
I don't want to sound like an elitist, but I think a big factor of why this is such a widespread issue is because people only think of music under broad umbrella terms, rather than according to genre or structure. Pic heavily related.

No one with even a passing interest in electronic music would sincerely tell you hard house and psychedelic trance sound the same. That doesn't even make sense! But the people who say things like this don't understand what the purpose of a bridge is, they literally have no idea why dance songs build up to the drop instead of immediately starting with it. They really think that because you can't hear the bass in heavy metal music, that means it serves no purpose. Hell, this is why sub bass is seen as superior to analog or bass guitar, because NPCs think music is just something you put on to rattle speakers and get people "vibing" or whatever.

I'm not saying you have to be autistic about it, but I don't really think anyone, even anons on /mu/, actually sits down and listens to music for the music itself. Obviously there's no way to prove this, but it's something I think will become an issue for music as its own medium in the future.

>So, you're saying there is a correct way to listen to music?

Yes, exactly, and it's not something we learn by taking a class, we're born with this ability and very few use it to its fullest extent. It's entirely possible that the reason NPCs can't visualize food and have internal monologues is because of apathy, they don't KNOW what talent they possess as humans because there has never been a situation where that was necessary for them. Similarly, what incentive do people have to actively listen to music? If this isn't the case, then I think the world is gonna be fucked as more music is made only for passive consumption, similar to how a lot of TV shows just kind of come and go without any lasting impact on people.

>>114607628
I guess I don't understand how you're not being a music theorist yourself with what you're saying. your complaint (if I understand it correctly) is that people don't pay enough attention to the nuances of music - for instance not recognizing the interplay between parts, or paying specific attention to genre and structure. those are all under the umbrella of "music theory," which encompasses much more than just chord progressions and modes. you also say there's a right way to listen to music (which is active listening), which I don't necessarily agree with but does fall outside of that music theory umbrella I suppose.

but I disagree. you could just as easily argue that because music is one of the oldest forms of art right along side cave painting and storytelling, that we've lost something because it no longer fills its ceremonial role. we don't sing together as people nearly as often; we don't have live musicians in our ceremonies; armies don't march in to battle to the beat of a drum. Or you could say that because for so long music held a special religious role and now it doesn't, that music is no longer primarily a collective experience to put in us the feeling that we are nearer to God, that this is the issue with people's understanding of and response to music. I disagree with both of those assessments too, but they're other ways of looking at the issue you present which is that people don't actively listen to music or have it effect them profoundly.

overall, it seems like you're frustrated because people around you don't "get" it in the same way you do - which isn't a crazy frustration to have. But to say its because people are incapable (either because of their choices of because of society) I think is a gross misunderstanding.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114614114
It won't help at all to try to learn those from that sheet. Start playing songs with complicated chords and learn those chords within a musical context. I'm assuming you're a jazz player, in which case you will realistically learn new voicings when you get comfortable with the ones you have and get bored. This is how most guys did and do it. Learn based on necessary rather than attempting to have total knowledge of guitar that's divorced from the actual music.
The last thing I'll add is you will probably naturally come across most of these with adequate fretboard knowledge or a good ear. It's not hard to come up with 10 or 20 ways to play C11 for example when you understand what C11 is and where all the C,E,F,G, and potentially Bb's are on the fretboard. This is much more valuable than a single voicing and is more natural.

>>114598735
Don't expect a rock album. I know that sounds obvious but it took years for TBHC to click for me because I was expecting a slow build into a fast, rapid, and climactic finish at the end. But its not about that. Instead, try and enjoy the ride. Songs like Star Treatment do have a loud "YEAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAH" at the end, but for me I find the peak of the song to be "Lounge singer shimmer". And for Batphone (the song that made TBHC click for me) it was really getting into the flow of the song that made the second "I'll be by the BATphone" resonate with me. At least for me, this is the mental change I had to make before I could really understand TBHC

posts.com: My G string intonates badly on the first three frets and buzzes above the 10th fret, any idea why that might be? The action isn’t significantly higher or lower than the adjacent strings, which haven’t got either issue

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114616469
If it's top 3 frets, chances are your nut action is too high. Go to your garage and find a .020 thou feeler gauge. Slide it between the string and first fret. If it can ring out a note, it's too high. If vibrates it's perfect. If the string is just laying flat against it, it's too high. Also the fret buzz means you have a high fret.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114616469
set it up fresh
1. remove strings
2. get neck dead straight with zero tension, notched fretboard rulers are 10 dollars on amazon
3. add strings tune to pitch
4. set string height to 4/64ths at 12th fret
5. play, if you are buzzing on low frets loosen truss rod
in my experience, trying to measure relief with feeler gauge is waste of time. usually if it's dead straight at no tension, with strings on it should automatically give you the slight bow necessary. should barely be any gap
do not do the "Fender 0.010 at 8th fret with feeler gauge" thing because that is WAY too much relief. you want as little relief as possible for maximum sustain and playability

posts.com: Why do you think so? I love it because it feels like a very wholesome album but with bittersweet moments roused from the band's personal trials at the time. It has Wayne finally finding a way to express himself as clearly as possible and rein in the more obnoxious tendencies of his creative spirit. Also the album easily has the best drum recording and mixing I have probably ever heard. Drozd's drums thunder and dominate the mix but don't come as irritating, more satisfying and celebratory than anything. I'm not a big fan of Fridmann's style but he really succeeded on this one. It's an inimitable album that stands alone in my mind.

On January 20, SM Entertainment announced its plans to instate a revised management structure in 2023.

Previously, SM Entertainment worked with its shareholder Align Partners Capital Management to introduce revision campaigns to the agency's internal management structure. According to the agency on this day, SM Entertainment and Align Partners came to an agreement on 12 clauses through which the entertainment company's management structure will be revised, with many of the changes taking effect after the company's general board meeting, convening in March of 2023.

Notably, president Lee Chang Hwan of Align Partners will be appointed a board director at this general board meeting in March, with various other internal changes gradually shifting the structure of SM Entertainment to a global governance format. Important to this change will be the founding of a committee for internal exchange, which will closely monitor and investigate past and future internal financial exchanges.

Additionally, beginning in 2023, SM Entertainment will adopt a multi-producing system, enlisting numerous talented producers in the mission to inherit, sustain, and evolve the musical identity of SM Entertainment and its artists. It seems that through this multi-producing system, SM Entertainment will no longer rely completely on head producer Lee Soo Man for the creative direction of all music projects.

Finally, on behalf of co-presidents Lee Sung Soo and Tak Young Joon, SM Entertainment assured that all conflict with its external shareholders have now been resolved through its recent agreement with Align Partners Capital Management.
